definition.value: A glycolipid and which the glyco component is specified as galactosyl.
A glycerol ether having at least one alkyl substituent on oxygen.
An acyl derivative of phosphatidic acid whose phosphorus acid component is esterified with an N-(2-hydroxyethyl)pyridinium bisretinoid
The stable isotope of copper with relative atomic mass 62.929601, 69.2 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 3/2.
The parent compounds of the ceramide family, composed of sphingosine having an unspecified fatty acyl group attached to the nitrogen.
An organic group that consists of a closed ring. It may be a substituent or a skeleton.
A cationic phosphosphingolipid consisting of sphingosine having a phosphocholine moiety attached to its primary hydroxyl group.
The biological role played by a material entity when bound by a receptor of the adaptive immune system. Specific site on an antigen to which an antibody binds.
A galactose phosphate compound with undefined anomeric stereochemistry having L-configuration and the phosphate group at the 1-position.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of lysine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of lysine by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing lysine residues.
A polymer composed of repeating ethylamine units.
A halophenol in which the halogen atom is bonded to the carbon atom adjacent to the C-OH group.
The amino acid zwitterion formed from 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine by tranfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the amino group. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
A polymer carrying multiple negative charges.
Any fatty acid containing at least one C=C double bond.
A drug that binds to and activates gamma-hydroxybutyric acid receptors.
A macromolecule containing ionic groups.
An alpha-D-glucoside deoxygenated at C-2 and C-6.
A tetracyclic antibacterial agent derived from neomycin, being a glycoside ester of neamine and neobiosamine C.

A 29-amino acid peptide hormone consisting of His, Ser, Gln, Gly, Thr, Phe, Thr, Ser, Asp, Tyr, Ser, Lys, Tyr, Leu, Asp, Ser, Arg, Arg, Ala, Gln, Asp, Phe, Val, Gln, Trp, Leu, Met, Asn and Thr residues joined in sequence.
A monocarboxylic acid that is the 3-O-methyl ether of (3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)acetic acid. It is a catecholamine metabolite.

A dialdehyde that is propane substituted by two oxo groups at the terminal carbon atoms respectively. A biomarker of oxidative damage to lipids caused by smoking, it exists in vivo mainly in the enol form.

A singly-charged anionic phospholipid that is the conjugate base of 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoserine, in which the carboxy and phosphate groups are anionic and the amino group is cationic; major species at pH 7.3.
Tetraanion of coenzyme A.
An acyl-CoA(4-) that is the tetraanion of acetyl-CoA, arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups.
A ribonucleoside triphosphate oxoanion that is the trianion of adenosine 5'-triphosphate arising from deprotonation of three of the four free triphosphate OH groups.
An amino acid zwitterion arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of glycine.
The dicarboxylate anion of protoporphyrin, obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups.
A prostaglandin carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of prostaglandin F2alpha, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of sarcosine; major species at pH 7.3.
Dianion of 10-formyltetrahydrofolic acid arising from deprotonation of both carboxylic acid functions.
Trianion of UTP arising from deprotonation of three of the OH groups from the triphosphate moiety.
Zwitterionic form of carnosine.
An anionic form of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide arising from deprotonation of the two OH groups of the diphosphate moiety.
A fatty acid anion with a chain length of C13 to C22.
Trianion of GTP arising from deprotonation of three of the four phosphate OH groups.
Dianion of CDP-ribitol arising from deprotonation of both free diphosphate OH groups.
The zwitterion of a phosphatidylethanolamine compound formed by proton transfer from the phosphate to the primary amino group.
Zwitterionic form of gamma-amino-beta-hydroxybutyric acid having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group.
Dianion of UDP-alpha-D-xylose arising from deprotonation of both free diphosphate OH groups.
The conjugate base of a 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine compound formed by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group.
Anionic form of chondroitin D-glucuronate arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid groups of the repeating units; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained via global deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 3,4-bisphosphate.
Dianion of UDP-N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosamine arising from deprotonation of both free diphosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.
